Q1. What is the hierarchy of the InputStream and OutputStream classes?
-->InputStream and OutputStream are the two root abstract classes in Java's byte stream hierarchy. They are part of the java.io package and 
    are used to read and write binary data (such as images, audio, videos, PDFs, etc.).
    
    InputStream → Used to read bytes from a source.
    OutputStream → Used to write bytes to a destination.
    
    Since they are abstract classes, we cannot create their objects directly. Instead, we use their subclasses.

    Hierarchy of InputStream:
    -------------------------
                        Object
                       │
                InputStream (abstract)
                       │
 ┌─────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────┐
 │                     │                             │
FileInputStream   ByteArrayInputStream      PipedInputStream
 │
BufferedInputStream
 │
DataInputStream
 │
ObjectInputStream


    Important subclasses
    --------------------
    FileInputStream → Reads data from a file.
    BufferedInputStream → Improves reading performance using a buffer.
    DataInputStream → Reads primitive data types (int, double, boolean, etc.).
    ObjectInputStream → Reads serialized Java objects.
    ByteArrayInputStream → Reads data from a byte array.
    PipedInputStream → Reads data sent from another thread.



    Hierarchy of OutputStream
    -------------------------
                        Object
                       │
               OutputStream (abstract)
                       │
 ┌─────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────┐
 │                     │                             │
FileOutputStream  ByteArrayOutputStream     PipedOutputStream
 │
BufferedOutputStream
 │
DataOutputStream
 │
ObjectOutputStream
 │
PrintStream


Important subclasses
FileOutputStream → Writes data to a file.
BufferedOutputStream → Improves writing performance using a buffer.
DataOutputStream → Writes primitive data types.
ObjectOutputStream → Writes serialized Java objects.
PrintStream → Prints formatted data (e.g., System.out).


Interview Points (Very Important)
---------------------------------
InputStream and OutputStream belong to the java.io package.
They are abstract classes.
They work with byte streams (8-bit data).
Used for binary files like images, PDFs, audio, videos, etc.
InputStream is for reading data.
OutputStream is for writing data.
They provide common methods like:
read()
write()
close()
flush() (only in OutputStream)


Example:
--------
import java.io.FileInputStream;
import java.io.FileOutputStream;
import java.io.InputStream;
import java.io.OutputStream;

public class ReadAndWriteFile{
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        try{
            InputStream in = new FileInputStream("data.txt");
            OutputStream outV = new FileOutputStream("vowels.txt");
            OutputStream outC = new FileOutputStream("consonents.txt");
            OutputStream outD = new FileOutputStream("digits.txt");
            OutputStream outS = new FileOutputStream("special.txt");

            int data;
            while((data = in.read()) != -1){
                // char ch = (char) data;
                if((char)data == 'A' || (char)data == 'E' || (char)data == 'I'|| (char)data == 'O'|| (char)data == 'U' || (char)data == 'a' || (char)data == 'e' || (char)data == 'i'|| (char)data == 'o'|| (char)data == 'u' ){
                    outV.write((char)data);

                }else  if(Character.isDigit((char)data)){
                    outD.write((char)data);

                }else  if(  !Character.isDigit((char)data)  && !Character.isLetter((char)data) && !Character.isWhitespace((char)data)){
                    outS.write((char)data);

                }else{
                    outC.write((char)data);
                }
            }


        }catch(Exception e){
            e.printStackTrace();

        }


    }
}





Q2. What do you understand by an I/O stream in Java?
-->An I/O (Input/Output) Stream in Java is a sequence of data used to read input from a source or write output to a destination.
    It provides a way for Java programs to communicate with files, the keyboard, memory, networks, and other devices.
        
        Input Stream → Reads data into a Java program.
        Output Stream → Writes data from a Java program to a destination.
        Types of I/O Streams
        Byte Streams
        Used for reading and writing binary data (images, videos, PDFs, etc.).
        Base classes:
        InputStream
        OutputStream
        Character Streams
        Used for reading and writing text data.
        Base classes:
        Reader
        Writer
        Example
        import java.io.*;
        
        public class Main {
            public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
                FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("input.txt");
                int data;
        
                while ((data = fis.read()) != -1) {
                    System.out.print((char) data);
                }
        
                fis.close();
            }
        }
        Interview Definition (2–3 lines)
        
        An I/O stream in Java is a flow of data between a Java program and an external source or destination. It is used to read input and write output.
        Java provides byte streams (InputStream/OutputStream) for binary data and character streams (Reader/Writer) for text data.






Q3. What are FileInputStream and FileOutputStream in Java?
-->FileInputStream and FileOutputStream are classes in the java.io package used to perform file operations using byte streams.

        FileInputStream → Reads bytes from a file.
        FileOutputStream → Writes bytes to a file.
        
        They are subclasses of InputStream and OutputStream, respectively.
        
        Example
        FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("input.txt");
        FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream("output.txt");
        Use Cases
        Images
        Audio
        Videos
        PDFs
        Text files (although FileReader/FileWriter are preferred for text)
        Interview One-Liner
        
        FileInputStream is used to read bytes from a file, while FileOutputStream is used to write bytes to a file. Both are subclasses 
        of InputStream and OutputStream and belong to the java.io package.




Q4. What are the different ways to take input from the console in Java?
-->Java provides several ways to take input from the console.
        
        Scanner (Most commonly used)
        BufferedReader
        Console
        DataInputStream (Old, rarely used)
        1. Scanner
        Easy to use.
        Can read different data types.
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        
        int n = sc.nextInt();
        String name = sc.next();
        2. BufferedReader
        Faster than Scanner.
        Reads input as text (String).
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
        
        String s = br.readLine();
        3. Console
        Used mainly for password input.
        Available only when running from a real console.
        Console c = System.console();
        
        String name = c.readLine();
        char[] pwd = c.readPassword();
        4. DataInputStream (Legacy)
        Older approach.
        Rarely used in modern Java.
        DataInputStream dis = new DataInputStream(System.in);
        
        String s = dis.readLine();   // Deprecated
        Interview One-Liner
        
        The common ways to take console input in Java are Scanner, BufferedReader, Console, and DataInputStream (legacy). Among these, 
        Scanner is the most commonly used, while BufferedReader offers better performance.




Q5. What is the difference between DataInputStream and BufferedInputStream?
-->
| `DataInputStream`                                                         | `BufferedInputStream`                                      |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- |
| Used to read **primitive data types** (`int`, `double`, `boolean`, etc.). | Used to **improve reading performance** by buffering data. |
| Reads data in Java's binary format.                                       | Reads raw bytes efficiently.                               |
| Provides methods like `readInt()`, `readDouble()`, `readBoolean()`.       | Provides methods like `read()`, `available()`.             |
| Used when data was written using `DataOutputStream`.                      | Used to reduce the number of disk I/O operations.          |
| Focuses on **data format**.                                               | Focuses on **performance**.                                |

    DataInputStream
    
    DataInputStream dis = new DataInputStream(new FileInputStream("data.dat"));
    
    int n = dis.readInt();
    double d = dis.readDouble();
    
    BufferedInputStream
    
    BufferedInputStream bis = new BufferedInputStream(new FileInputStream("data.txt"));
    
    int ch = bis.read();
    Interview One-Liner
    
    DataInputStream is used to read Java primitive data types from a stream, whereas BufferedInputStream is used to improve input performance 
    by reading data through an internal buffer.




Q6. Why are InputStream and OutputStream abstract classes, not interfaces?
-->InputStream and OutputStream are abstract classes because they provide both method declarations and common implementations that
    all subclasses can reuse.
        
        If they were interfaces, every subclass would have to implement all the methods from scratch (before Java 8).
        
        Examples of implemented methods
        
        InputStream provides methods like:
        
        read(byte[] b)
        read(byte[] b, int off, int len)
        close()
        
        These methods already have implementations.
        
        Subclasses like FileInputStream only need to implement the core method:
        
        read()
        
        Similarly, OutputStream provides implementations for methods like:
        
        write(byte[] b)
        write(byte[] b, int off, int len)
        close()
        flush()
        
        while subclasses mainly implement:
        
        write(int b)
        Interview One-Liner
        
        InputStream and OutputStream are abstract classes because they provide common implementations of methods that can be shared by
        all subclasses, reducing code duplication while still forcing subclasses to implement the core read/write operations.




Q7. What is the difference between flush() and close()?
-->
| `flush()`                                                                            | `close()`                                                      |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Writes any buffered data to the destination.                                         | Writes any remaining buffered data and then closes the stream. |
| The stream **remains open**.                                                         | The stream is **closed** and cannot be used again.             |
| You can continue writing after calling `flush()`.                                    | You cannot read/write after calling `close()`.                 |
| Used when you want to ensure data is written immediately without closing the stream. | Used when you are completely done with the stream.             |

    Example:
    FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream("data.txt");
    
    fos.write("Hello".getBytes());
    
    fos.flush();   // Data is written, stream is still open
    
    fos.write(" World".getBytes());
    
    fos.close();   // Writes remaining data and closes the stream
    Interview One-Liner
    
    flush() forces buffered data to be written while keeping the stream open, whereas close() flushes any remaining data and then closes
    the stream permanently.



Q8. What does ObjectOutputStream do? (Used for serialization.)
-->ObjectOutputStream is a class in the java.io package used to serialize Java objects.

        Serialization is the process of converting an object into a byte stream so that it can be:
        
        Stored in a file.
        Sent over a network.
        Saved in a database (as binary data).
        
        The object must implement the Serializable interface.
        
        Example
        import java.io.*;
        
        class Student implements Serializable {
            int id = 101;
            String name = "John";
        }
        
        public class Main {
            public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        
                ObjectOutputStream oos =
                        new ObjectOutputStream(new FileOutputStream("student.dat"));
        
                Student s = new Student();
        
                oos.writeObject(s);
        
                oos.close();
            }
        }
        Key Method
        oos.writeObject(object);
        
        This method serializes the object and writes it to the file.
        
        Interview One-Liner
        
        ObjectOutputStream is used to serialize Java objects by converting them into a byte stream, allowing them to be stored in a file or
        transmitted over a network. The object's class must implement the Serializable interface.



Q9. What is the difference between FileWriter and PrintWriter?
-->
| `FileWriter`                                        | `PrintWriter`                                                       |
| --------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Used to write **characters** to a file.             | Used to write **formatted text** to a file or other output streams. |
| Mainly writes raw character data.                   | Can write text, numbers, booleans, objects, etc.                    |
| Does not provide `print()` and `println()` methods. | Provides `print()`, `println()`, and `printf()` methods.            |
| Best for simple file writing.                       | Best for formatted and user-friendly output.                        |

